From 496fe0259c42288bf21c6cb7e6d9340a67e32b29 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Ilya Gulya <ilya@gulya.me>
Date: Sun, 28 Jun 2026 05:21:03 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] dar-6x4: don't hold Process::_rwlock across suspending dtape
 calls in notifyCheckin

Fork+exec storms (e.g. `make -jN` of many small compiles, libunistring/gettext
builds) intermittently WEDGE darlingserver: rpcs_serviced goes flat, every guest
hangs in recvmsg, and the server never recovers. This was previously misfiled as
mere slowness; it is a real deadlock.

Root cause (pinned live with gdb): notifyCheckin()'s exec branch holds the
per-process std::shared_mutex _rwlock across dtape_task_create /
dtape_thread_create / dtape_semaphore_* , which can SUSPEND the microthread
(they enter duct-taped XNU code that blocks on a waitq/lock). _rwlock ownership
is per-OS-THREAD, but perf #2b (dar-dar6x4-perf-5dq.8) runs cheap RPCs INLINE on
the MAIN event-loop thread while a suspended microthread resumes on the WORKER.
So when an exec checkin runs inline on MAIN and suspends, the write lock is left
stranded owned by MAIN; a sibling's fork-checkin then runs on the single WORKER
and blocks forever in _notifyListeningKqchannels() taking the SAME process lock
for read -- and the only thread that could resume the lock-holder is that
now-stuck worker. gdb at the wedge: __cur_writer == MAIN tid, worker blocked in
pthread_rwlock_rdlock (__readers = WRLOCKED|WRPHASE). Pre-#2b this could not
happen: every microthread ran on the single worker, so a process lock was always
acquired and released on the same OS thread.

A/B confirmation (heavy fork+exec load): pristine inline-on -> WEDGED on attempt
1; forcing all calls to the worker pool (no inline) -> 20/20 builds clean; this
fix with inline left ON -> 20/20 builds clean. So the fix removes the deadlock
without giving up the perf #2b inline win.

Fix: in the exec branch, drop _rwlock around the dtape create/destroy/release
calls and re-acquire it to publish the new task/thread/semaphore handles -- the
same pattern the thread-clear loop just above already uses around the blocking
notifyDead(). Safe to drop: all other threads are already cleared (only the main
thread remains in _threads), _pendingReplacement stays true, and the swapped
dtape handles are not traversed by _rwlock readers.

RED->GREEN regression test committed alongside the fix
(tests/inline_suspend_rwlock_deadlock.c + runner): models a process rwlock held
by one OS thread across a "microthread" suspension while another OS thread takes
it for read. RED arm (held across suspend) deadlocks (watchdog, exit 1); GREEN
arm (released before suspend = this fix) passes. HOST test, <5s.

bead: dar-6x4 (epic dar-dar6x4-perf-5dq)
